Bring a large #saucepan{} of water with @salt{1/2%tsp} to the boil for the potatoes.

Chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2cm chunks (peel first if you prefer).

When boiling, add the potatoes to the water and cook until you can easily slip a knife through, ~{15-20%minutes}. Once the potatoes are cooked, drain in a #colander{} and return to the pan, off the heat.

Add a knob of @butter{knob} and a splash of @milk{splash} (if you have any) and mash with a #potato masher{} until smooth. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cover with a #lid{} to keep warm.

In the meantime, halve, peel and chop the @onion{1}(peeled and chopped) into small pieces.

Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves}(grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Roughly chop the @dill{1}(roughly chopped, stalks and all).

Crumble the @Greek Style Salad Cheese{50%g}(crumbled).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @Diced British Chicken Thigh{260%g} and onion. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Fry until the chicken is golden brown on the outside and cooked through, ~{8-10%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging. It's cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Stir through the garlic, @Lemon & Herb Seasoning{1%tbsp} and @Plain Flour{1%tbsp}. Cook for ~{1-2%minutes} - you want all the veg and chicken to be coated in the flour.

Add the @Water{250%ml}, @Chicken Stock Paste{15%g} and @Peas{120%g}. Simmer until the sauce has thickened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Meanwhile, set your #grill{} to the highest setting.

Once the sauce has cooked, taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed. Stir through half the dill.

Gently stir the remaining dill and crumbled Greek salad cheese through the mash.

Pour the chicken mixture into an appropriately sized #ovenproof dish{}, then carefully spread over the potato mash.

Grill until the mash is golden, ~{6-8%minutes}.

Once assembled, share the potato topped pie between your plates. Enjoy!